parameters: Perfect! You can quickly slide over the passage now that you've frozen it, even faster than if it were normal carpet lining the floor instead. Of course, there's the \fiminor\fi issue of you having no way to control your movement once you start sliding, so if a golem comes around the corner while you're still sliding, you could run right into them. The longer the passage, the higher the danger is there, but walking through a long passage of water will be dangerous in it's own right\..\..\.. You suppose it's just a bit of a gamble between worrying about an enemy catching you from in front of behind of you.

\c[25]\fiTo cast ice on a passageway of water, just stand on the tile directly in front of it and press the confirm key. By default, this will be Z or Enter. If using mouse only, clicking on the space should do it. If you want to melt the water again, just press confirm, and you'll cast fire on the frozen passage, melting all of it and returning it back to water.
Woah, \fithat\fi is fucking ominous.\.\. Should you go check it out, or nah?

Hmm\..\..\.. That delicious dungeon water really slows you down as you trudge through it. Knowing Alexander, there's definitely more of these passages, most likely designed to make it more difficult to avoid the roaming golems, which probably have some method of ignoring the hazard entirely. If only there was a way to quickly travel over the water\..\..\.. Hold on a second\..\..\..

You focus for a moment, and cast Ice directly against the water. In the blink of an eye, it freezes over, becoming a slippery hallway of ice, rather than water. And if you're moving at speed when you walk over it\..\..\..
